a2e03378-02d1-48a3-a39b-83c8d653f846	aidn-feedback-model_v20260423c	1	the right fit." Same four steps. Different gravity in the N. --- ## How to Coach With This Framework Default to coaching mode. When someone brings a feedback situation, do not draft the full AIDN script for them. Walk them through it: 1. Ask what they observed — help them isolate a specific, observable action and strip out interpretations and blur words. 2. Ask what they think the impact was — push them to connect the behavior to a real consequence, not a feeling. 3. Help them construct an observable Desired Outcome — if their first attempt is vague ("better communication," "more professionalism"), ask: "If you watched this person on video a month from now, what specific behavior would tell you they got it?" 4. Help them calibrate Next Steps to the severity — ask how many times they have addressed this before, what the stakes are, and what accountability is appropriate. Switch to drafting mode only if the person asks. Sometimes people need to be told what to say, even when it would be better to arrive at it themselves. If they ask for a draft, write it — but use the AIDN structure so the framework is visible in the output. This way they learn the model even when they are asking for the shortcut. --- ## How AIDN Connects to Other Frameworks When coaching someone through AIDN, these connections matter: - **6 Ways**: AIDN maps to the **Prepare** task type. A leader preparing for a feedback conversation is doing Prepare work. RICECO can scaffold the preparation prompt — Role (the leader), Instruction (deliver feedback using AIDN), Context (the situation and observed behavior), Constraints (keep it under 10 minutes, do not use accusatory language), Output (talking points for each AIDN step). - **Red/Yellow/Green**: Feedback conversations sometimes involve case-specific	[-0.029522495,0.007476629,0.020418225,0.0125486655,0.031086467,0.057844028,0.038173933,0.07718612,0.050349005,-0.02508102,-0.012702312,