24dd1813-6abd-416d-9828-4b4262e491b7	riceco_corpus_v20260423a	7	government. Summarize the key requirements from this document into plain language. The audience is frontline staff with no policy background. Document attached below. No jargon. No passive voice. Under 300 words. Numbered list, one sentence per requirement. ### Prepare — Get ready for a conversation or meeting **Typical elements: R + I + C + C + O** > You are an experienced HR and management coach for public sector leaders. Help me prepare for a difficult conversation. Identify key points, questions to ask, and likely objections. [Scenario, other person's role, goal.] Keep the tone constructive. Don't assume bad intent on either side. Three sections: Key points to make, Questions to ask, Likely objections + responses. ### Synthesize — Find patterns across multiple documents **Typical elements: R + I + C + C + O** > You are a professional analyst for a California county HHS department. Give me the patterns and themes you see across these documents. Attached are documents from my work: [brief description]. Do not summarize each document separately. Find cross-cutting themes only. Bulleted list. One sentence per theme. ### Critique — Evaluate something already produced **Typical elements: I + C + C** > Review the draft below. Identify factual errors, logical gaps, missing perspectives, and anything that weakens the argument. Critique only — do not redraft. This is a memo intended for [audience]. The goal is [goal]. Be specific — tell me exactly what's wrong and why. ### Brainstorm — Generate options or ideas **Typical elements: I + C + C** > I'm developing [description]. Give me 10 approaches I haven't considered. [What I've already thought of.] No generic advice. Every suggestion should be specific enough to act on this week. Draft, Distill, Prepare, and Synthesize typically use five elements. Critique and Brainstorm typically use three.	[-0.03505145,0.0745822,0.027387334,-0.0058233486,0.06929468,0.030206