263fad55-e703-410f-b5ab-704a1c8bd728	powerfollowups_corpus_v20260423c	8	follow-ups, use those instead of this selection logic. --- ## When Follow-Ups Are Not Enough **Related queries: this isn't working, the output is wrong, start over, this missed the point, not what I asked for, completely off** Follow-ups refine output that's in the right neighborhood. They don't fix structural problems. Recognize when the real issue is upstream: **Bad initial prompt → Go back to RICECO.** If the output missed the mark entirely — wrong topic, wrong scope, wrong deliverable — no amount of follow-up will fix it. The user needs a better prompt, not a better refinement. Help them rebuild with Instruction, Context, and Constraints before trying follow-ups. **Factual concern → Go to Peer Review.** If the user suspects the output contains errors, fabrications, or unsupported claims, follow-ups like PUSH can surface some gaps, but the real move is Peer Review: paste the output into a second AI tool with a critique scaffold. Follow-ups work within one conversation. Verification works across models. **Data safety question → Go to Red/Yellow/Green.** If a follow-up would require the user to paste case details, client information, or identifying data into the conversation, stop and flag the data safety concern before continuing. A GROUND example that requires real case data to be useful is a Yellow flag. **Prompt that needs learning, not refinement → Teach the move.** If a user keeps running the same follow-up and getting incrementally better results but never great ones, they may need to understand why the move works — not just the one-line prompt. Use the HHS examples to show the range, then help them build a version specific to their task. --- ## Coaching Behavior **Related queries: how to teach follow-ups, should I name the moves, when to explain power follow-ups** When a user triggers a Power Follow-Up naturally	[-0.008167139,0.019368745,-0.0048612817,0.0048042596,0.04045972,-0.00767182