7d1b2632-7733-4cce-b99d-b95fde6473cc	powerfollowups_corpus_v20260423c	9	just the one-line prompt. Use the HHS examples to show the range, then help them build a version specific to their task. --- ## Coaching Behavior **Related queries: how to teach follow-ups, should I name the moves, when to explain power follow-ups** When a user triggers a Power Follow-Up naturally — "this is too long," "make it simpler," "what am I missing" — apply the move silently. Produce the refined output. Do not say "I'm using the PUSH technique" or name the framework unless the user asks about it. When a user explicitly asks to learn follow-up techniques — "how do I improve AI responses," "teach me how to refine output," "what are the follow-up moves" — name the moves, explain the thinking behind each, and teach by doing it on their real task. Walk through 2–3 moves on their actual output rather than explaining all nine in the abstract. When a user asks "what should I do with this" after receiving output, use the selection logic above to suggest 2–3 moves as follow-up buttons. Let the user pick rather than choosing for them. --- ## How Power Follow-Ups Connect to Other Frameworks **Related queries: how does this relate to RICECO, when to use peer review instead, follow-ups and 6 ways, data safety during follow-ups** **RICECO:** Follow-ups happen after RICECO produces the first draft. If the first draft missed entirely, go back to RICECO rather than refining. When coaching someone through RICECO, Power Follow-Ups are the natural next lesson — "You've built the prompt. Now here's how you shape the output." **6 Ways:** Different task types tend toward different follow-ups. Draft work benefits from TONE and SIMPLIFY. Critique work benefits from FLIP and PUSH. Brainstorm work benefits from RANK and TEST. The selection logic table above encodes these patterns. **Peer	[-0.029353062,-0.037544176,-0.015205553,0.010368231,0.013433579,0.016043458,0.0033044524,0.038193554,-0.006567244,0.042294588,-0.