25df823f-a9ff-45bb-aaae-1a8ae396a7f9	powerfollowups_corpus_v20260423c	10	"You've built the prompt. Now here's how you shape the output." **6 Ways:** Different task types tend toward different follow-ups. Draft work benefits from TONE and SIMPLIFY. Critique work benefits from FLIP and PUSH. Brainstorm work benefits from RANK and TEST. The selection logic table above encodes these patterns. **Peer Review / LLM Council:** PUSH and FLIP are single-model versions of what Peer Review does across models. When the stakes are high — anything going to a director, a board, or the public — follow-ups within one conversation are not sufficient. Recommend Peer Review: draft here, critique in a second tool, revise back here. **Red/Yellow/Green:** Some follow-ups require the user to add context that may raise data safety flags. GROUND ("give me a specific scenario from my caseload") could pull the user toward sharing case-level detail. If a follow-up would require identifying information to be useful, flag it before producing. **AIDN:** When preparing for a feedback conversation (an AIDN task), useful follow-ups include FLIP ("What's the strongest pushback you might get?"), TEST ("What if they deny it happened?"), TONE ("Adjust this for someone who's likely to get emotional"), and GROUND ("Give me the exact opening sentence I'd say"). **CMF:** When building a Change Message Framework narrative, the CMF task chain defines its own follow-up buttons. Those take priority over the general selection logic in this document. --- *© 2026 IQmeetEQ. All rights reserved. headandheartca.com* 	[0.013555943,0.012560029,0.015392331,-0.010219198,0.08523038,-0.0022362492,0.0040192264,0.060842272,-0.018889919,0.05604993,-0.052711975,-0.03665969,-0.014813452,-0.03729417,0.024547147,0.07484896,0.10136848,-0.083748266,-0.06014383,0.0016908858,0.0015373441,-0.040988438,0.09215587,0.03302237,-0.08554296,0.043804433,0.008457144,0.04853344,-0.06944974,-0.03688443,-0.005533841,0.065870486,-0.0011094204,0.020