5f1b2797-0b5e-4cfc-95a3-b2705544cd57	llmpeerreview_corpus_v20260423c	0	# LLM Peer Review: Draft, Verify, Revise **Corpus Document | Category: Methodology** **Retrieval targets: verify, check my work, peer review, LLM council, second opinion, is this accurate, review my draft, check this for errors, did the AI get this right, is this good, can you check this, review what I wrote, proof this, proofread, hallucination, made something up, wrong date, wrong statute, fabricated, before I send this** --- AI is confident whether it's right or wrong. It doesn't know the difference. That means verification is your job — and the best way to verify AI output is to use a different AI to check it. This is LLM Peer Review (formerly called LLM Council): Draft in one tool, Verify in another, Revise based on what you find. --- ## Why This Works Every AI tool has different training data, different strengths, and different blind spots. When you ask a second tool to review what the first one produced, you surface errors, gaps, and assumptions that the original tool will never catch on its own — because it doesn't know they're there. A single AI tool will defend its own output. It generated the text, so when you ask "is this right?" it's biased toward saying yes. A different tool has no loyalty to the original draft. It reads it cold. This is the same reason peer review works between humans. The person who wrote the memo is the worst person to proofread it. --- ## Why This Matters in HHS Work AI fabricates with the same confidence it uses when it's right. In HHS, a fabricated statute number in a board memo, a wrong effective date in a staff briefing, or an invented eligibility threshold in a training document doesn't just embarrass you — it can trigger wrong case decisions,	[-0.08011587,0.022329796,-0.029379029,0.0052832025,0.08805648,-0.032028347,-0.001373391,0.00581371,0.03367182,0.07022875,-0.028162902,0.0011014988,0.07378625,-0.03997724,-0.07293122,0.02131968,0.051086698,0.049285267,