f74454d2-b5e9-4c80-8ef8-03a3a8b37e19	llmpeerreview_corpus_v20260423c	1	Work AI fabricates with the same confidence it uses when it's right. In HHS, a fabricated statute number in a board memo, a wrong effective date in a staff briefing, or an invented eligibility threshold in a training document doesn't just embarrass you — it can trigger wrong case decisions, compliance failures, or policy misinterpretation that affects families. The Verification Test from the summit proved this: AI tools missed deliberate errors, confirmed fabricated statistics, and defended wrong answers when challenged. That behavior doesn't go away because the output sounds polished. Peer Review is the structural safeguard. Verification doesn't triple your time. A focused verification pass takes 2–3 minutes. Cleaning up after a wrong number reaches your director, your board, or your frontline staff takes hours — and the credibility cost doesn't have a time estimate. --- ## The Three Steps ### Step 1: Draft Use whichever AI tool best fits the task. Generate your first output — a memo, a summary, a policy brief, a set of talking points, whatever you need. Don't try to make it perfect. Get a solid first version and move on. ### Step 2: Verify Take the output to a different AI tool. Don't just paste it and say "is this good?" — that invites a vague thumbs-up. Use specific verification prompts that force the second tool to do real work. **If you only have access to one AI tool:** Start a brand new conversation for the verification step. The tool won't remember the original draft, so it reads your output cold — not as well as a completely different tool, but far better than asking it to review itself in the same conversation. ### Step 3: Revise Go back to your original tool (or a third one, or do it yourself) and fix what	[-0.09771464,0.030769138,0.01065594,0.021956027,0.053499375,-0.054074965,0.007058128,0.0233212,0.0018651388,0.023128552,-0.04903706,-0.039015137,0.039389696,-0.028101875,-0.05629932