cea48f70-808d-45e6-afc7-a097fe42a2cb	llmpeerreview_corpus_v20260423c	4	to decide. Two tools gave you the information. Now it's your call. --- ## When to Use LLM Peer Review Not every task needs it. Here's how to decide: **Always use it when:** - The output will be read by people outside your immediate team — directors, board members, partner agencies, families - It contains statute numbers, ACL references, deadlines, eligibility criteria, or fiscal figures - It will be used in a decision-making context — board presentations, budget justifications, policy recommendations, county plan amendments - It involves any content about families, cases, or services — even if anonymized - It will be shared with frontline staff as procedure or guidance — errors here multiply across every worker who follows it - You're less familiar with the subject matter than your audience is - It will go to CDSS, CWDA, a court, county counsel, or the media **Probably fine to skip when:** - You're brainstorming for yourself and won't share the output - You're using AI to organize your own notes or thinking - The output is a first draft you'll heavily rewrite anyway - You're generating a format (table, checklist) from content you already verified --- ## Common Mistakes **Asking the same tool to check itself.** "Review what you just wrote" is not verification. The tool is biased toward its own output. Use a different tool — or at minimum, a new conversation. **Pasting without a specific ask.** "Is this good?" will get you "Yes, this looks great!" every time. Give the verifier a job: check facts, find gaps, challenge the logic, assess the tone. **Treating verification flags as orders.** The second tool might be wrong too. It might flag something that's actually correct. You're the decision-maker — verification gives you information, not instructions. **Skipping verification because the first draft	[-0.049171153,0.045331623,-0.07696182,-0.020251425,0.03847824,-0.019384421,0.07404364,0.029285371,0.03