9fe668a7-fb81-4e4e-8d81-75a71b7b4d72	llmpeerreview_corpus_v20260423c	6	it's for), Constraints (don't confirm things just because they sound right). When you write a verification prompt, you're using RICECO whether you call it that or not. **Red/Yellow/Green:** The verification step has its own data safety dimension. If your original draft contains case details, client information, or sensitive operational data, pasting it into a second AI tool means that data now lives in two tools' processing pipelines instead of one. Apply the same Red/Yellow/Green judgment to what you paste into the verifier. Strip identifying information before sending a draft for review — the verifier doesn't need client names to check your logic. **Power Follow-Ups:** Two Power Follow-Up moves are verification moves by another name. Push ("What's missing in your response?") and Flip ("Make the strongest case against this") do verification work inside the same conversation. They're lighter than a full LLM Peer Review — useful for medium-stakes work where a new-tool review feels like overkill. --- ## Using This Chatbot as Your Verifier If you drafted something in another AI tool — ChatGPT, Gemini, Copilot, or anywhere else — you can paste it here and ask for a review. **What this chatbot can check:** Whether your draft aligns with responsible AI use in county HHS work, whether the structure and framing follow sound methodology, whether the tone fits your audience, and whether there are gaps in your argument or approach. This chatbot is grounded in HHS-specific frameworks and workflows. **What this chatbot cannot check:** Factual accuracy of policy citations, whether a specific statute number is correct, or whether statistics in your draft are real. For factual verification, use a general-purpose AI tool with web search enabled, or check the source documents directly. Try: - "I drafted this in ChatGPT. Check it for anything that doesn't align with responsible AI use	[-0.087515846,0.006359497,-0.0