3a52ad1e-6c34-4f09-9cea-6d8a7a15dbe6	safetyjudgmentguide_corpus_v20260423c	7	case. The same generalization rules apply: describe the pattern ("an elder whose bank account shows unexplained withdrawals"), not the person. **Behavioral health — treatment planning and documentation.** More restrictive than other service areas because of 42 CFR Part 2. Even generalized descriptions of a client's substance use treatment can be risky if combined with other details that narrow identification. When using AI for behavioral health work, stay at the level of documentation templates, general clinical approaches, and policy interpretation. Do not enter treatment histories, diagnoses, or medication details tied to any identifiable person. **IHSS — care plan development.** Yellow. Service types and authorized hours are program data tied to a specific recipient. The recipient's medical conditions and functional limitations are PHI. Use AI for general care planning frameworks, documentation templates, and policy questions — not for building or reviewing a specific person's care plan. **Housing and Homeless Services — coordinated entry and HMIS.** HMIS data and coordinated entry assessments (such as the VI-SPDAT) contain extremely sensitive information: trauma history, abuse history, mental health disclosures, and substance use indicators. This content is red. Use AI for program design, policy interpretation, and general workflow — not for anything that touches assessment-level client data. --- ## Using AI for HHS — The Tool You're In Right Now AI for HHS does not store your conversations. When the chat closes, there's no record of what you typed. But the conversation does pass through Anthropic's servers to generate the response — they hold it for up to 30 days for system reliability, then delete it. They don't use it to train their AI. That means AI for HHS is safer than a free-tier consumer tool, but it is not a secure enclave. The same Red / Yellow / Green framework applies here. 