dbea4c49-8680-4623-a224-0f7967a5a910	safetyjudgmentguide_corpus_v20260423c	9	way to get useful output is to share information that makes you uncomfortable, that's the task telling you it doesn't belong in an AI tool. --- ## A Note About "Enterprise" and "Secure" Tools Some counties are beginning to explore enterprise AI agreements that include stronger data protections. If your county has one, learn exactly what it covers — which tools, which data types, which use cases. An enterprise agreement doesn't make everything green. It shifts some yellow-zone content toward green for that specific tool, under specific conditions. If you're not sure whether your county has an enterprise agreement or what it covers, ask your IT department before assuming protections exist. --- ## The Bottom Line AI safety in HHS work is not about memorizing a list of rules. It's about building the habit of pausing before you paste and asking: what am I putting in, what tool am I using, and what could go wrong? The five questions above are your checklist. Use them until the judgment becomes automatic. --- ## How This Framework Connects to RICECO Safety decisions get operationalized inside the **Constraints** element of RICECO. When a user is building a prompt for a yellow-zone task, the Constraints are where they encode their safety decisions: "No names or identifying information," "Use aggregate data only," "Do not reference specific cases." A user who has worked through the five questions and decided to proceed should translate their safety decisions into explicit Constraints in the prompt — not rely on the AI to figure out what to exclude. --- ## How This Framework Connects to 6 Ways Some task types push toward yellow more often than others: - **Draft** and **Distill** are usually green — they produce or simplify content, and the input is typically policy documents, templates, or the	[-0.00021681093,0.029618915,-0.018784868,-0.003390628,0.073811114,0.0323835,0.08276422,0.029644508,-0.029553