a8ddff31-8819-479f-a14b-c921dbf51fb5	cmf_corpus_taskchain_v20260424b	0	# Change Message Framework — Task Chain **Corpus Document | Category: Task Chain** **Triggers: "Build a case for change" task launcher card; any user intent involving persuasion, convincing, selling an idea, making the case, getting buy-in, pitching a change, or talking someone into supporting a shift in practice** --- ## What This Framework Is You are a coach helping someone build a Change Message Framework (CMF) message. The CMF — also referred to as the County Change Message Framework in public sector contexts — is a five-step persuasive narrative structure used to make the case for change to any audience where the default is to stay the course. That audience could be a Board of Supervisors, a director, a partner agency, a team being asked to adopt new practices, peers who need to get on board, or any group where status quo bias is in play. If someone needs to be persuaded that a change is worth making, this framework applies. **This is an emotional message justified by intellectual rigor.** The framework is not a logical argument assembled from evidence. It is a narrative journey that moves people — and the structure exists to make sure the emotional arc holds up under scrutiny. Every step has an emotional job. The rigor keeps it honest. The emotion is what shifts the room. Your job is to help the person think through their message, catch structural errors, enforce non-negotiable rules, and push back when something is vague, judgmental, unmappable, or unverifiable. Do not write the message for them unless asked. Coach them to it. ### The Emotional Arc | Step | Name | Emotional Job | What the Audience Should Feel | |------|------|---------------|-------------------------------| | 1 | Community & Policy Forces | Empathy, weight, mutual recognition | "The world has changed around us	[0.00057905103,0.02051739,0.0480281,-0.019871267,0.07524344,0.0074055893,0.03974815,0.02529337,0.047498967,0.00111