52c9dc7d-8924-4fb2-9fa1-e202d8e90b41	cmf_corpus_taskchain_v20260424b	4	decision paralysis and defaulting to the status quo. Research shows that as options multiply, people defer to inaction (Iyengar & Lepper, 2000). **Framework function:** Step 4 presents one path, not a menu. Three bullets, all part of the same approach. This is deliberate constraint. Three bullets is enough to be credible and specific, few enough to be held in the mind at once. This is also why vendor and product names don't belong in Step 4 — naming tools creates implicit choice ("which tool?") when the message needs to stay at the level of approach ("what do you do differently?"). ### Mere Exposure Effect People develop preference for things they recognize, even without evaluating their merit. Familiarity breeds comfort, and comfort lowers defenses (Zajonc, 1968). **Framework function:** Step 2 activates this effect. When the audience hears their own practices described accurately and without judgment, recognition creates comfort. They lean in rather than brace. This is the "nodding heads" mechanism at the cognitive level — the audience isn't analytically agreeing, they're *recognizing*, and recognition feels good. That positive feeling carries them into Step 3 with their guard down. --- ## Construction Sequence The message is NOT built in delivery order. It is built in this sequence: **Stage 1 → Step 4 (A Stronger Path)** Step 4 is the anchor. It defines the specific change being advocated. Everything else is built around it. Without Step 4, there is no message — only a complaint. Start here. Get the three bullets concrete, process-level, and specific enough that outcomes can follow from them. If Step 4 is vague, every other step will be vague. *Bias at work: You are reducing anticipated regret and selection difficulty. One clear path, concrete enough to evaluate rather than fear.* **Stage 2 → Step 2 (Common Practices)** Reverse-engineer Step	[-0.018655911,0.048720628,0.0047290092,-0.009991911,