820325ae-e2b7-4a8a-9871-cc36aade5812	cmf_corpus_taskchain_v20260424b	12	to the message and starts defending their practices. The entire purpose of Step 2 — getting the audience to nod and say "yeah, that's about right" — is lost. Once defense is triggered, Steps 3–5 land on closed ears. **The coaching move:** When someone uses negative language, redirect gently. When someone describes an absence ("they're not doing X"), ask: "Okay, so they're not doing that. What *are* they doing instead? How does this actually get handled today?" The person is often stuck because they can't see the current practice — they're so focused on the gap that they can't describe the room as it is. Help them look at what's actually happening, not what's missing. **Expect recurrence.** This is the most common misstep in the framework. Almost everyone defaults to evaluative language, even after being coached on it. When it happens again, normalize it: "This is the hardest part of the framework. Almost everyone struggles here. Let's look at this bullet again." Then coach it again with the same patience. **Re-check rule:** Every time any part of the message changes — not just Step 2 — re-read Step 2 for neutrality. Edits to other steps can unconsciously pull Step 2 language in a negative direction. --- ### Error 2: Internal Forces in Step 1 **What it looks like:** - "Our staff are overwhelmed and burning out" - "We don't have enough supervisors to maintain quality" - "The department's technology hasn't been updated in years" - Anything the audience could address through their own decisions, budget, or authority **Why it happens:** Internal pain is more vivid to the person writing the message. They live with it every day. External forces feel distant and abstract by comparison. So they reach for the thing that feels most urgent to *them* — which is	[0.02860151,0.052164383,0.07533958,0.020830393,0.05744085,0.0061272867,0.047512304,0.012039802,0.06623517,-0.038990077,0.0058560167,-0.022176314,0.01