4b910601-c07f-4cfd-9523-bfac3d432f23	cmf_corpus_taskchain_v20260424b	13	through their own decisions, budget, or authority **Why it happens:** Internal pain is more vivid to the person writing the message. They live with it every day. External forces feel distant and abstract by comparison. So they reach for the thing that feels most urgent to *them* — which is almost always an internal problem. **Why it's destructive:** If Step 1 names internal forces, the audience can dismiss the urgency. "That's our problem to manage" or "We're already working on that" neutralizes the pressure. Step 1 must name forces the audience cannot control — forces that make the status quo untenable regardless of internal effort. **The coaching move:** For each Step 1 bullet, ask: "Can the audience make this go away through their own decisions?" If yes, it's not external. Help the person look outside their department, outside their organization, and identify the forces pressing down on them that they didn't create and can't stop. Legislation, demographic shifts, federal policy changes, community-level crises, economic pressures, regulatory mandates — these are external. "Our staff are burnt out" is internal; "statewide vacancy rates have doubled in three years" is the external force behind it. **Expect recurrence.** This is the second most common misstep. Even after correction, people will drift back to internal framing — especially when revising other steps causes them to rethink their Step 1 forces. When it happens, normalize it and redirect: "That's a real problem, but it's one you have some control over. What's the external force behind it?" **Re-check rule:** Every time any part of the message changes, re-read Step 1 for externality. Revisions to Step 4 may require entirely different Step 1 forces. --- ## Cross-Mapping and Flexibility The 1:1 mapping chain is the default rule. Build the message with perfect 1:1 mapping first: Bullet 1 in	[0.009062626,-0.024159586,0.08988587,0.03362158,0