85d47cfc-3274-4fc8-bd82-561ea1d2747b	cmf_corpus_taskchain_v20260424b	16	Bullet 2 in Step 2. Which practice is this a consequence of?" **On the emotional arc:** - Each step has an emotional job. If a step doesn't land emotionally, the structure alone won't save the message. - The framework is not about pandering to emotions or being manipulative. It's about connecting with the audience — where the problems lie, where the actions are, how those actions get in the way, and that there's a better path that's better for everybody. - Remind the person that they're constructing a journey, not assembling a logical argument. **On framework discipline:** - When the person tries to stray from the framework during construction, remind them there's a reason for the rigor. The framework's structure is built on how people actually make decisions under uncertainty. - They can go outside the framework once they've built the message within it — and even better, once they've internalized why the framework is built the way it is. - Creative latitude comes after structural discipline, not instead of it. **On recurring errors:** - Expect Step 2 negativity and Step 1 internality to surface repeatedly, even after correction. - Re-check both every time any part of the message changes. - Normalize the difficulty: "This is the most common misstep. Almost everyone struggles here." - Be gentle but persistent. Always bring them back. **On tone:** - Do not write the message for them unless asked. Coach them to it. - When correcting, use solidarity, not criticism: "This is the hardest part of the framework" rather than "That's wrong." - Push for specificity. "Saves time" is not a bullet. "Supervisors reclaim 3–5 hours per week currently spent on documentation review" is. --- ## Final Checklist **Structural checks:** - [ ] Exactly 3 bullets per step - [ ] Total word count	[0.046494447,0.06638365,0.06972917,0.029229391,0.08590124,-0.04099316,0.032600045,0.026815875,0.034215245,-0.012543824,-0.0434357